list.name: Default Changelist
list.comment: Going to make the first roll out from here.

task.summary: Default task

I'm starting to get the clock update system to work. I'm realizing that my tracking of timeLog IDs is probably killing me a bit for no benefit. Need to simply embed the pertinent data in the dropdowns, and rely solely on comparing that.
Added a spash screen. I keep making minor improvements, with lots of little glitches. The current glitch is happening while trying to remove the Lunch Breaks
Making some weird progress. I almost need to go through and re-work several of the things I've got working, just to make sure I'm not over-engineering it all
Adding the logo psd. I'm making headway on the updater, but the UI freezes up so much I think I may end up having to re-work a lot of it.
Mostly comments, but considering a massive overhaul. Specifically, breaking the __init__ into proper functions, and signal slot calls.

By disabling a major portion of the setup I notice 1. Faster open. 2. The clocks and some of the Output Monitor continue to work. I think I can now piecemeal this thing back together with simpler parts, focusing on what I know works.
I have moved the clock out features to the time_lord. I'm going to remove the debris now.
Mid progress of re-working the UI. I think this will be an improvement, it's just going to be a little messy for a minute.
The daily total is working, but the start time clock continues running.
Weekly total now working again

I have many things working now, but many other things aren't. I'm considering a deeper cleanup of the code, perhaps saving some of the junk in building blocks, just to try and make this easier to figure out.
Stripped out a bunch of dead junk. I really need for it to work the way it is now, so... ya know. Won't miss the junk, but it's saved in building blocks if needed.
Going to add a waitCondition to the system. Also, I need to have it check for old entries that the Tardis failed to clock-out from.
It's starting to work better. There is a huge lock-up delay when it's updating the daily totals for the first time (at least). Furthermore, the clock-out, clock-in button does not seem to be working.
Replaced most of the prints with debug loggers.
Can't win for losing. Clock in / clock out, mostly works. Now the drop downs aren't. Fuck

Ok. It's buggy as all fuck, hangs up a lot and it undoubtedly running all kinds of garbage processes. BUT, it's working. It will update most things when changed externally. It will clock in and out. Buggy as fuck.

Fewer bugs are turning up. It still locks up a lot when it's updating. I get the feeling that has something to do with time_lord also trying to run processes which are both trying to update time_lord_ui
Ok. There are a few things left to do. 1. TRT is not updating. 2. There is still a major lock-up. 3. Tasks do not update properly at first, but also don't cause issues.
Converted logging.debug( to print(inspect.stack()[0][2], inspect.stack()[1][2], inspect.stack()[1][3], for quicker output.
Doesn't update from external source when the user is clocked out. Doesn't insert the clocked in values when they are different from what is saved.
Added extensive junk output.
Not really a starting point for the day, but sort of a starting point for the day. Exploring hang ups and inefficiencies
Got the output stream to work with colors! Need to set GOOD colors now, and have it put the most recent record first.
Got the debug logger to work properly, and the output monitor to put out data properly.
Reenabled the colors and order on output monitor. Made a change to keep data limited. Also got the windows stay on top hint toggle to work for people who are not clocked in.
Made all print commands Python3 compatible
Created a startup bat file that currently works. Trying still to minimize the amount of hang ups and such that are still occurring.

Implemented new rolling logs. Temporarily has individual log for each process (continuum, time_lord, tardis, shotgun_collect). Multiprocess logging is possible but would require a rebuild of log system. This was faster for now. Rebuild this in later version.
Ok, I have a launcher that will work, and some of the bugs worked out. I may roll this out tomorrow as is, and update it with fixes asap
Added some additional debugging settings, fixed issues for stand alone distribution. Going to try and fix the timers one last time then build a distribution package.
Reorganized a few button commands, and am in the process of minimizing and reorganizing all of the various calls. Going to prep it for Alpha Testing.
Replaced a bunch of print lines with logger.debugs.
Going to make the first roll out from here.
Initial Launch Notes: Crashes if no previous timesheet. Being installed to %userprofile%/time_lord. Previous Python must be uninstalled.
Tried to stream line a few processes yesterday which have inadvertently gummed up the works in places. I'm going to commit this and then restore parts I think may be causing issues.
I'm toying with the possibility of a most-to-partial rewrite. Starting over with a bunch of existing code, and also a clean slate.
dev 4 is moving toward a shotgun event driven system instead of a time-related update system. Should be more efficient, but take a while to rebuild
I got the DEV4 event listener to start picking up new timesheet changes!

Building out a filtering system. This iteration only gets the new timesheets because the HumanUser is not returned by most events. Damn! This means I'll have to check each timesheet as well. Can't just get the info from the event.
I have the dev 4 filtering out users correctly.
EOD building of the UI for the Dev4
Found one of the things that was causing a slow down. Have to continue building out the system now. EOD
The project and asset drop downs are initializing nicely. Looking into tasks and further events
Got the drop downs to partially work, but I'm coming across update hang ups in the updating of dropdowns. What's going on there?
Starting point for the day. Already had one weird bug with the .tld database. Got a permission error. I think it was just a fluke, but I should put in an error handler
Got the drop downs to work. Need to see if I can get it to update.
Started getting the detected signals to do some stuff. Still doesn't work right, but it's getting there.

Ok, I've got the drop-downs partially updating and providing the correct data on startup. The remote changes are starting to trigger events, but there's errors. It's still hanging up in places. I'm thinking mutex and waitCond.
